    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right; chlorosis can sometimes be caused by nitrogen deficiency, which is why the leaves might be pale as well. To ensure your tomato plants can absorb nutrients more effectively, you'll want to check and adjust the soil pH. Tomato plants thrive in slightly acidic soil, with a pH between 6.0 and 6.8. If your soil is too alkaline, you can lower the pH by adding organic matter like compost or by using sulfur-based amendments. On the other hand, if your soil is too acidic, you can raise the pH by adding lime. Remember, it's important to test your soil pH regularly and make adjustments gradually to avoid shocking your plants. And don't forget, maintaining a balanced soil ecosystem is key to preventing nutrient-related issues, so keep your soil healthy with proper composting and mulching.",
